          <div class="project-details">
            <div class="detail-block">
              <h4>Architecture</h4>
              <p>PentAGI (CT 198, pve2) runs 4 Docker containers: Go backend + React UI, PostgreSQL with pgvector, a Playwright-based web scraper, and on-demand Kali Linux worker containers for executing offensive tools. LLM inference runs locally on the RTX 3090 via Ollama &mdash; zero API cost, zero data leaving the network.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="detail-block">
              <h4>First finding: CrowdSec LAPI exposure</h4>
              <p>The very first scan targeted Traefik (192.168.1.110). PentAGI's agents discovered port 8081 (CrowdSec LAPI) was listening on <code>0.0.0.0</code> instead of <code>127.0.0.1</code> &mdash; accessible from the entire LAN. Not critical (token-protected), but unnecessary attack surface. Fixed immediately: <code>listen_uri: 127.0.0.1:8081</code>. The tool paid for itself on day one.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="detail-block">
              <h4>Companion: PentestAgent MCP</h4>
              <p>For interactive CTF sessions, PentestAgent runs inside the Kali distrobox and connects to Claude Code via MCP (STDIO). During Hack The Box sessions, Claude can directly invoke pentest tools &mdash; nmap, sqlmap, hashcat &mdash; through natural language. Two tools, two modes: autonomous audit (PentAGI) and guided pentest (PentestAgent).</p>
            </div>
