      <div class="container">
        <div class="project-header">
          <span class="project-tag">IoT</span>
          <h2>LoRa + MQTT + Home Assistant — Physical world meets homelab</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="project-body">
          <div class="project-intro">
            <p>Two Meshtastic T-Beam LoRa nodes, a Mosquitto MQTT broker, and Home Assistant. The homelab's first physical layer &mdash; radio mesh networking independent of all Internet infrastructure.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="project-details">
            <div class="detail-block">
              <h4>Architecture</h4>
              <p>T-Beam 2242 (CLIENT) sends LoRa packets at 868 MHz to T-Beam 8181 (ROUTER_CLIENT), which bridges them to Mosquitto (CT 142) via MQTT over WiFi. Home Assistant (VM 140, HAOS) subscribes and processes the telemetry. First test: RSSI &minus;55 dBm, SNR 12.5 dB &mdash; excellent signal indoor. Channel encrypted with AES-256, private key.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="detail-block">
              <h4>The debugging chain</h4>
              <p>Mosquitto 2.x defaults to localhost-only &mdash; had to bind <code>0.0.0.0:1883</code>. File ownership on <code>/etc/mosquitto/passwd</code> was root instead of mosquitto &mdash; crash exit 13, silent. HAOS behind Traefik returns HTTP 400 until <code>trusted_proxies</code> is configured. And HAOS breaks every homelab pattern: no SSH, no Ansible, no systemd &mdash; it's its own ecosystem.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="detail-block">
              <h4>Why LoRa</h4>
              <p>WiFi goes down when the router restarts. 4G depends on a carrier. LoRa at 868 MHz works with zero infrastructure &mdash; two nodes and physics. Range: kilometers outdoor, buildings indoor. The last-resort communication layer if everything else fails.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="project-stack">
